{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CFYw7u9uFTPGkp2B9knUvd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture:\n\n1. The ConfigMap `mongodb-config` has key `mongod.conf` with the current configuration:\n   - `systemLog.verbosity: 1` → needs to become `2`\n   - `operationProfiling.slowOpThresholdMs: 200` → needs to become `400` (2x)\n   - `storage.wiredTiger.engineConfig.journalCompressor: snappy` → needs to become `zlib`\n\n2. The annotation shows the original applied ConfigMap was missing the systemLog, operationProfiling, and wiredTiger sections - these were added later by someone (the prevalue ConfigMap shows the \"original\" values were verbosity=1 and slowms=200, consistent with current config).\n3. The StatefulSet mounts this ConfigMap at `/etc/mongodb/config/` and starts mongod with that config file. The reminder warns that the key might have been removed externally, so I need to verify the mongod.conf actually exists in the ConfigMap and that the pods can access it properly.\n\nLooking at the data, I can see `mongod.conf` is present with the full configuration including the keyFile path, storage settings, and replication config. Comparing the annotation (which shows the last-applied configuration) to the current state, I notice the current ConfigMap has additional sections like wiredTiger, systemLog, and operationProfiling that weren't in the original applied config—so the ConfigMap has actually been updated since it was created.\n\nNow I need to make three specific changes: bump the systemLog verbosity from 1 to 2, double the operationProfiling slowOpThresholdMs from 200 to 400, and switch the wiredTiger journalCompressor from snappy to zlib. After updating the ConfigMap, I'll need to restart the StatefulSet pods since ConfigMaps mounted as volumes don't automatically reload.\n\nFor a 3-member replica set, I should restart one pod at a time to maintain availability, wh